verbose_text: miRNA (miR)-15/16, miR-34 and the miR-200 family are reported to have inhibitory effects on lung cancer; the overexpression of miR-15/16 inhibited non small cell lung cancer cell proliferation and invasion by regulating TWIST1; miR-17-92, miR-222/221 and miR-155 were found to promote the progression of breast cancer, and miR-17-5p promoted breast cancer cell invasion and migration through the inhibition of HMG box containing protein 1.
